    <content type="html">&lt;div class="sidebar"&gt;
  &lt;figure&gt;
    &lt;img src="/images/2015-08-26-textures-and-abstract-imagery/inverse_leaves.jpg" /&gt;
    &lt;figcaption&gt;Leafs inverted&lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In limba romana: etc etc a photograpy, it is said, can tell more than a thousand words. Yes, I agree but how ? It seams to me that we interpret it in an instant with a deeply rooted empathy and we build the narative in our minds with minimal verbalization by putting in motion or simply analysing what we see. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In grapic design we use images. They can play a central role in the work being done, or secondary, just siding or mixed with written content, almost always to convey the intended message. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But what happens when you putt abstract images into graphic design work ? The grip on meaning loosens allowing for a more subjective interpretation of what is looked at. This I suppose, imposes a certain mood on the viewer affecting the way he feels about the larger context. Abstract images play on emotion. It is like this how we make sense of things we see and we don&amp;rsquo;t understand, we feel in a certain way about them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lately I become very fond of abstract photography and have made a little collection of them that now, I am glad to share with you. These images are taken (and sometimes edited) with my phone, a HTC m8. I make this available for everybody to use as they wish in their graphic design work. Maybe you want to share your creations with me reach me out on twitter &lt;a href="http://www.twitter.com/@nedzen"&gt;@nedzen&lt;/a&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;

